## Components all the way down

In Module 1.2, you learned that a React component is a function that returns JSX. Now here is the key insight that makes React powerful: **components can use other components inside their return statement**.

This is called **composition**, and it is how every React page is built. A page is not one giant file of markup. It is a tree of small, focused components, each responsible for one piece of the interface.

Here is a simple example:

```jsx
function Header() {
  return (
    <header className="site-header">
      <h1>My App</h1>
      <nav>
        <a href="/home">Home</a>
        <a href="/about">About</a>
      </nav>
    </header>
  );
}

function Footer() {
  return (
    <footer className="site-footer">
      <p>&copy; 2025 My App</p>
    </footer>
  );
}

function Page() {
  return (
    <div className="page">
      <Header />
      <main>
        <h2>Welcome to the app</h2>
        <p>This is the main content area.</p>
      </main>
      <Footer />
    </div>
  );
}
```

Look at the `Page` component. Inside its return statement, you see `<Header />` and `<Footer />`. These are not HTML elements -- there is no HTML tag called `<Header>` or `<Footer>`. They are **React components**. When React encounters `<Header />`, it calls the `Header` function, gets back the JSX it returns, and inserts that JSX in place of the `<Header />` tag.

The result is as if `Page` had written all the markup inline:

```html
<div class="page">
  <header class="site-header">
    <h1>My App</h1>
    <nav>
      <a href="/home">Home</a>
      <a href="/about">About</a>
    </nav>
  </header>
  <main>
    <h2>Welcome to the app</h2>
    <p>This is the main content area.</p>
  </main>
  <footer class="site-footer">
    <p>&copy; 2025 My App</p>
  </footer>
</div>
```

### The capital letter rule

How do you tell the difference between a React component and a regular HTML element when reading JSX? The rule is simple and absolute:

- **Capital letter** = React component (defined somewhere in the codebase)
- **Lowercase letter** = standard HTML element

```jsx
return (
  <div>                    {/* HTML element */}
    <Header />             {/* React component */}
    <main>                 {/* HTML element */}
      <ArticleList />      {/* React component */}
      <Sidebar />          {/* React component */}
    </main>
    <footer>               {/* HTML element */}
      <Copyright />        {/* React component */}
    </footer>
  </div>
);
```

This is one of the most useful literacy skills you can develop. When scanning unfamiliar React code, the capitalization immediately tells you which pieces are custom-built and which are standard HTML.

### The component tree

When you nest components inside each other, you create a **component tree** -- a hierarchy that describes the structure of the page. Here is a realistic example of what a dashboard page might look like as a tree:

```
App
├── NavBar
│   ├── Logo
│   └── UserMenu
├── Dashboard
│   ├── MetricsRow
│   │   ├── MetricCard ("Revenue")
│   │   ├── MetricCard ("Users")
│   │   └── MetricCard ("Orders")
│   ├── RecentActivity
│   │   └── ActivityItem (repeated)
│   └── QuickActions
└── Footer
```

And here is how the top-level component might look in code:

```jsx
function App() {
  return (
    <div className="app">
      <NavBar />
      <Dashboard />
      <Footer />
    </div>
  );
}
```

The `App` component does not know what is inside `NavBar`, `Dashboard`, or `Footer`. It just knows they exist and arranges them on the page. Each of those components manages its own content. `Dashboard` might contain `MetricsRow`, `RecentActivity`, and `QuickActions`. `MetricsRow` might contain three `MetricCard` components.

This is the power of composition: each component is small and focused, and the page structure emerges from how they are combined.

### Where to find a component's definition

When you see `<Sidebar />` in a component, you might wonder: where is `Sidebar` defined? The answer is almost always at the top of the file, in an **import statement**:

```jsx
import Sidebar from "./components/Sidebar";
import Header from "./components/Header";
import UserProfile from "./components/UserProfile";

function DashboardPage() {
  return (
    <div>
      <Header />
      <div className="content">
        <Sidebar />
        <UserProfile />
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

The import tells you the file path. `import Sidebar from "./components/Sidebar"` means there is a file at `./components/Sidebar.js` (or `.jsx` or `.tsx`) that exports the `Sidebar` component. If you want to understand what `<Sidebar />` renders, you go to that file.

This is how you navigate a React codebase: see a component tag, check the import, follow it to the file.

### A real-world example

Here is a simplified version of what a settings page might look like in a real React app:

```jsx
import PageLayout from "../layouts/PageLayout";
import SettingsNav from "./SettingsNav";
import ProfileSection from "./ProfileSection";
import NotificationSettings from "./NotificationSettings";
import DangerZone from "./DangerZone";

function SettingsPage() {
  const user = { name: "Maria Lopez", email: "maria@example.com" };

  return (
    <PageLayout title="Settings">
      <div className="settings-container">
        <SettingsNav />
        <div className="settings-content">
          <ProfileSection user={user} />
          <NotificationSettings />
          <DangerZone />
        </div>
      </div>
    </PageLayout>
  );
}

export default SettingsPage;
```

Without knowing anything about the internals of these components, you can read this page:

- The page is wrapped in a `PageLayout` that handles common layout structure
- There is a `SettingsNav` for navigation between settings sections
- The main content area has three sections: profile, notifications, and a danger zone (probably for account deletion)
- The `ProfileSection` receives the user data -- the other sections do not need it
- Each component lives in its own file (visible from the imports)

This is React literacy in action: you can understand the structure and purpose of a page without reading the implementation of every component.

### Components can appear multiple times

A component is reusable. You can use the same component multiple times with different data:

```jsx
function TeamPage() {
  return (
    <div className="team">
      <h1>Our Team</h1>
      <MemberCard name="Alice" role="Engineer" />
      <MemberCard name="Bob" role="Designer" />
      <MemberCard name="Carol" role="PM" />
    </div>
  );
}
```

Three `MemberCard` components, each with different data. The component is defined once but used three times. This is one of the main reasons React uses components -- write the card layout once, reuse it for every team member.

